\details{
This function evaluates classification performance without simulation.
Given a set of decision cuts and conditional standard errors across
a fixed ability grid, classification accuracy and consistency are computed
analytically by integrating conditional classification probabilities over
a population ability distribution.

The procedure consists of the following steps:

\enumerate{
\item \strong{Define true classification levels:}
Each ability value \eqn{\theta}{\theta} on the evaluation grid is assigned to a
true classification level based on the specified cut theta values.

\item \strong{Compute conditional classification probabilities:}
For each \eqn{\theta}{\theta}, the probability of being classified into each level
is computed assuming a normal distribution for the reported ability
estimate:
\deqn{
    \hat{\theta} \mid \theta \sim \mathcal{N}(\theta,\ CSEM(\theta)^2).
  }

\item \strong{Conditional accuracy and consistency:}

Conditional classification accuracy is defined as
\deqn{P(\hat{C} = C \mid \theta)}
where \eqn{C}{C} is the true classification level.

Conditional consistency is defined as
\deqn{\sum_k P(\hat{C} = k \mid \theta)^2}
representing the probability that two independent parallel administrations
yield the same classification.

\item \strong{Marginalization over the population:}

Conditional indices are integrated over a population ability distribution
using externally supplied weights, yielding marginal classification
accuracy, marginal classification consistency, and a confusion matrix.
}
}
\section{Mathematical Formulation}{


Let \eqn{\theta_i}{\theta_i} denote an ability grid point and
\eqn{CSEM(\theta_i)}{CSEM(\theta_i)} the corresponding conditional standard error.
For classification cut scores \eqn{c_1, \dots, c_K}{c_1, \dots, c_K}, define level boundaries
\eqn{(-\infty, c_1, \dots, c_K, \infty)}{(-\infty, c_1, \dots, c_K, \infty)}.

The probability of classifying an examinee with true ability \eqn{\theta_i}{\theta_i}
into level \eqn{k}{k} is
\deqn{P(\hat{C} = k \mid \theta_i)}
\deqn{= \Phi(\frac{(u_k - \theta_i)}{CSEM(\theta_i)}) -
      \Phi(\frac{(\ell_k - \theta_i)}{CSEM(\theta_i)})}

where \eqn{(\ell_k, u_k)}{(\ell_k, u_k)} is the interval for level \eqn{k}{k}.

Conditional accuracy at \eqn{\theta_i}{\theta_i} is
\deqn{P(\hat{C}=C \mid \theta_i)}
and conditional consistency is
\deqn{\sum_{k=1}^{K+1} P(\hat{C}=k \mid \theta_i)^2}

Let \eqn{w(\theta_i) \ge 0}{w(theta_i) >= 0} be population weights on the grid, with
\eqn{\sum_{i=1}^{I} w(\theta_i)=1}{sum_{i=1}^I w(theta_i)=1}.

The marginal (population) indices are the
discrete weighted averages of the conditional quantities:

\deqn{MarginalAccuracy =
      \sum_{i=1}^{I} w(\theta_i)
      P(\hat{C} = C(\theta_i) \mid \theta_i)}

where \eqn{C(\theta_i)}{C(theta_i)} is the true level implied by \eqn{\theta_i}{theta_i} and the cut
scores.

\deqn{MarginalConsistency =\sum_{i=1}^{I} w(\theta_i) \sum_{k=1}^{K+1} P(\hat{C} = k \mid \theta_i)^2}

If \eqn{w(\theta_i)}{w(theta_i)} approximates a density \eqn{g(\theta)}{g(theta)}, these correspond to
the integrals \eqn{\int g(\theta)\,\cdot\, d\theta}{integral g(theta) dtheta}.
}

